=> Definition: CAP Theorem states that in the presence of a network partition, a distributed system can guarantee either Consistency or Availability, but not both. It is impossible to simultaneously guarantee all three of the following properties:
        -> C: Consistency
        -> A: Availability
        -> P: Partition Tolerance
    -> You can only fully guarantee at most two of them at the same time. Let's understand this with example:
    -> Assume your bank has 2 different server server A(Mumbai) and server B(Delhi) and data is replicated between them.
                          Client
                            |
                     -----------------
                     |               |
                 Server A  <------> Server B
                     (Balance = ₹1000)

    -> Consistency: All clients see the same latest data at the same time. You deposited 500 at Mumbai(Client → Server A).
                    After update Server A balance = ₹1500 & Server B balance = ₹1500
                    You can read from any server (Client → Server A → ₹1500 ✅, Client → Server B → ₹1500 ✅)
                            Client
                              |
                            Server A (₹1500)  <---->  Server B (₹1500)
                                    (perfect sync)
                    Without any delay update happens and this is called consistency.

    -> AVAILABILITY: It means every request get a response, no matter whether it is updated data or not server should be available.
                     For example in above case if server B is slow or overloaded, client might get older data i.e. 1000 not updated data i.e. 1500
                     So, client get response but data may not be latest and this is called availability.

    -> PARTITION TOLERANCE: System continues to work even when servers can’t communicate. It means network failure happen between the server but both server are up.
                            Now CAP decision happens, system must choose either availability or consistency.
                            -> Case 1️⃣: Partition + Consistency (CP System)
                                -> When a network partition occurs, a CP system prioritizes consistency by rejecting requests that cannot guarantee the latest data. The system sacrifices availability to maintain correctness.
                                                Network Partition Occurs
                                                ------------------------

                                                Server A   ❌❌❌   Server B


                                                Client → Server B
                                                           |
                                                      ❌ Reject / Timeout

                            -> Case 2️⃣: Partition + Availability (AP System)
                                -> When a network partition occurs, an AP system prioritizes availability by serving requests using local data, even if the data may be stale.
                                                Network Partition Occurs
                                                ------------------------

                                                Server A   ❌❌❌   Server B


                                                Client → Server B
                                                           |
                                                      ✅ Respond (Local Data)
                                                      ❌ May be stale


=> The Core Truth of CAP Theorem: When a network partition occurs, you must choose
        -> Consistency (CP) → Reject some requests
        -> Availability (AP) → Serve stale / conflicting data
    You can't have both.

=> Type of CAP System
    -> CP System (Consistency + Partition Tolerance): Chooses correctness over availability. If partition occurs, System may reject requests or return error/timeout
            -> Example: HBase, MongoDB (with majority writes), Zookeeper
            -> Used When: Banking, Payments, Inventory Count, Critical Correctness

    -> AP System (Availability + Partition Tolerance): Chooses availability over consistency. If partition occurs, System serves data and may be stale or eventually consistent
            -> Example: Cassandra, DynamoDB, CouchDB
            -> Used When: Social media feeds, Like/Comments, Product catalog, Analytics

    -> CA System (Consistency + Availability): Not possible in real distributed systems
            -> Because without partition tolerance the system fails as soon as network breaks.
            -> Works only in single node systems and non-distributed databases.
            -> So, When partition happens, system must choose between C or A.

=> In a distributed system, network partitions are unavoidable. During a partition, a system must choose between consistency and availability. The choice depends on business requirements.